{"/service/ndnp/ct/batch_ct_grasso_ver02/data/sn82014085/00393346978/1938010401/0028.xml":{"full_text":"NEW ACTIVITIES\nIN STEEL OPEN\nAT PITTSBURGH\nExecutive Offices Direct\nFar-Flung United States\nSteel Units\nBy JOHN B. DELANEY\n(United Press Staff Correspondent)\nPittsburgh, Jan, 4\u2014(UP)\u2014This\nWestern Pennsylvania metropolis to- j\nday claimed undisputed possession'\nof the title \"Steel Capital of the\nWorld,\u201d following decision of United\nStates Steel corporation to direct\nactivities of its far-flung subsidiaries\nfrom here.\nAnnouncement that headquarters\nof the newly-formed management\ncorporation\u2014United States Steel cor\nporation of Delaware\u2014would be es\ntablished here was considered the\nforerunner of a new era for Pitts\nburgh.\nAlthough incorporated in 1933. the\nnew company did not begin opera\ntion until New Year's day when 21\nsteel executives named as a board of\ndirectors moved here to take up\ntheir duties. Financial and policy\nproblems of U. S. Steel will continue\nto be formulated at the company's\nNew York headquarters.\nTaylor Hints as to Future\nWhen organization of the Dela\nware corporation was announced by\nMyron S. Taylor, retiring U. S. Steel\nchairman, in New Yor. one phrase\nof his statement was believed to in\ndicate possibility that all of the cor\nporation's activities eventually will\nbe directed from here. He said:\n\"The principal headquarters of the\nDelaware corporation will be at\nPittsbrugh. which is a central loca\ntion more convenient to the manage\nment of tire subsidiaries and more\ncloeely in touch with the atmosphere\nof steel operations.\n'This arrangement also will bring\nthe staff of the Delaware corpora\ntion into closer and more intimate\ncontact with current activities of\nsuch subsidiary companies.\u201d\nWhen United States Steel corpora- i\ntton was formed 40 years ago by J.\nP. Morgan and associates, manage\nment of a large segment of Pitts\nt orgh\u2019s blooming steel industry was i\nmoved to New Y'ork.\nOwned Wholly by V. S. Steel\nThe new Delaware corporation,\nwhich will be wholly owned by the\nparent concern. United States Steel\nof New Jersey, will supervise activi-:\nties of the following subsidiaries:\nCarnegie-Ulinois Steel corporation,\nlargest subsidiary: American Bridge;\nCo., American Steel and Wire Co..\nColumbia Steel company. H. C. Frick\nCoke Co.. Michigan Limestone and\nChemical Co.. National Tube Co.. Oil\nWell Supply Co., Oliver Iron Mining\nCo., Pittsburgh Limestone Co.. Pitts\nburgh Steamship Co., Scully Steel\nProducts Co.. Tennessee Coal, Iron\nand Railroad Co.. U. S. Steel Prod\nucts Co. and Union Supply Co.\nDirectors of the management con\ncern include William Beye, Chicago:\nA. N. Diehl. San Francisco; Robert\nGregg. Birmingham: B. F. Harris,\nMcKeesport, Pa.: C. F. Hood. Cleve\nland: M. D. Howell. Pittsburgh; G.\nC. Kimball, Chicago; Walter Math-\neslus, Chicago: C. V. McKaig, Pitts\nburgh; Thomas Moses. Pittsburgh:\nL. A. Paddock, Pittsburgh: J. L.\nPerry, Pittsburgh; C. H. Rhodes, i\nNew York; E. R. Stettinius, Jr., New\nYork, new chairman of board, U. S.\nSteel Corp.; E. M. Voorhees, New\nYork, and R. E. Zimmerman. New\nYork.\nJOHN T. FLYNN Charts Trade Year for The Democrat\ngwgtSPWH y y\nHow\u2019s Business?\nHere\u2019s Answer At a Glance\nThe business year 1937 has been graphically set forth in five basic charts prepared for\nNEA Service and The Waterbury Democrat by J ohn T. Flynn, noted writer on economic topics.\nThe reader who will follow these will see exactly what has happened to business, why it has\nhappened and what may be expected in 1938. The captions beneath the chart have been written\nby Flynn. i\nDepartment Store Sales\nmis cnart pictures reran sales, it snows two important facts.\n(1) There has been a steady rise since 1933 in peaks and valleys;\n(3) Retail trade rose during 1937. This shows that consumers, in\nspite of the business recession, kept up their buying right up to the end\nof November and that the recession did not begin with the customers.\nindustrial Production\n14(1\nThis chart shov/s clearly that production started its upward\nmovement in 1933 and kept on improving until May, 1937. The\nrecession began in production in May, 1937. It has declined ever since.\nThe year ended below the Christmas level. Why did production drop\nbefore retail sales?\nBuilding Contracts Awarded\n1930 1931 1932 1933 1934 1935 1936 1937\n3 This partly explains why production dropped before retail sales.\nThis chart shows how building construction has failed to develop.\nIt appeared to be improving since 1933. But the improvement was slight.\nThe highest point was a little over $320,000,000 in one month. This is\nless than half of the building volume of prosperous periods. And most\nof this, you will see, was public, not private building. Private building\nbegan a slight improvement in 1935. At the beginning of 1937 is seemed\nheaded for a burst of activity. But in April, just when it should have\nsoared upward, it faltered, declined and ended the year below the level\nof last year. This struck a blow to production in building material in\ndustries and generally sent a wave of feay through other producing in\ndustries. It frightened business men and obsdbvers; but consumers, who\ndo not pay much attention to such things, went on buying until the\nend of December.\nCommunities Planning\nFuture Water Supply\nRegardless of Business Conditions, Cities Must Anti=\ncipate Demands of Coming Years\u2014Lavery Talks\nRegardless of the present situa\ntion in business, water companies\nmust prepare far ahead to protect\nth* well-being and growth of the\ncommunities they serve, since con\nstruction of the water supplies takes\nseveral years and in the case of the\nSaugatuck Development of the\nBridgeport Hydaulic Company there\nis no assurance it will be built any\ntoo early to meet a demand which\nALBERT E. LAVERY\nVice President\nreal business recovery wiU exact,\nAlbert E. Lavery, vice-president ol\nthat company, stated today in sum\nmarizing the year-end situation in\nConnecticut's public water supplj\nindustry.\nMr. La very\u2019s statement follows:\n\"The business of furnishing water\nto a given community is different\nfrom almost every other business,\nIndustry is governed largely by de\nmand, and at some seasons of the\nyear this 1s greater than others, and\n'employment is affected accordingly.\nMany reasons have to do with the\nHow of employment and industry,\nbut with water it is largely a mat\nter of preparedness to meet the de\nmand. No water company can af\nford to be caught without adequate\nsupplj'. Therefore, regardless of\nconditions, the water company must\nanticipate its needs to prepare for\nthe future.\nSaugatuck River\n\"Bridgeport Hydraulic Company\nhas for many years had in mind the\ndevelopment of the Saugatuck river\nA\nI to augment our supply. It Is rather\nan expensive undertaking, especially\nwhen the many uncertainties to pre\nsent business are considered, but we\nknow that the need exists for it,\nand hope by spring to be in a posi\ntion to start active work. The new\nreservoir will impound about twelve\nbillion gallons of water and will be\nbrought into our present syptem by\na tunnel through Popp's Mountain.\nRegardless of the persent situation\nof business, we know from our ex\nperience that the dam will not be\nbuilt any too early to meet a de\nmand which a real business recovery\nwill exact, and besides, it will take\nseveral years to finish it.\n\"One thing about the water busi\nness is that its ability to furnish\nwater to communities is not com\nparable with any other. The amount\nof time involved to create a new\nsupply makes it imperative that suf\nficient water to meet any ordinary\ndemand must be at hand. A tem\nporary recession in business is only a\nwarning that the pendulum will\nswing back again, and cometlmes\neven farther than before. If you\nare not ready to meet any peak, you\nare not doing justice to the com\nmunity you serve because the failure\nof a water company to meet any de\nmand might stagnate the growth of\nthe community, and this must not\nhappen. Those entrusted to furnish\nj water supply to a given community\nrecognize this and act accordingly,\ni Most cities keep ahead of the parade\ni as far as water is concerned, and it\nis well that thi sshoulcl be, because\nwater is humanity's greatest need\nnext to the air we breathe.\u201d\nGIRL COMES OUT\nOF LONG COMA\nHartford, Conn., January 4.\u2014(UP'\nThe coma into which 7-year-old\nLillian Cote. Putnam, lapsed after\nan automobile accident December 2,\nwas broken today and physicians\nwere hopeful of her ultimate re\ncovoey.\nLillian ran into the side of an\nautomobile at Putnam while on her\nway to school with four other chil\ndren. Her skull was fractured and\nan immediate operation was per\nformed to relieve a brain pressure.\nI Last Friday she was transferred to\nSt. Francis hospital here for obser\nvation by specialists. Today she was\naroused from her leng sleep and it\nwas reported her condition was\n\"fairly comfortable\".\n7\nTWELVE BIG OIL\nTANKERS ON WAY\nStandard Oil Company to\nBuild Them for Use of\nGovernment\nWashington, Jan. 4.\u2014(UP)\u2014The\nUnited States maritime comission\nlias signed an agreement with the\nStandard Oil company for construc\ntion of 12 high speed oil tankers to\nbe used as auxiliaries for the navy\nm event of war, Chairman Joseph\nP. Kennedy announced today. Con\nstruction contracts totaling $31,556.\n004 have been awarded to shipyards,\nhe said. The government w\u2019ill pay\nI $10,563,000 for Inclusion of \u2018\u2018extras\" j\nto make the ships easily adaptable\nfor national defense purposes. The)\nI company will pay about $27,000,000\nof the construction cost and agrees\nto maintain the vessels in operating\ncondition at its own expense for 20\nyears.\nCarry 150,000 Barrels\nCommission experts said the new\nvessels would be built to carry 150,000\nbarrels of oil at a sustained sea\nspeed of 16 1-2 knots over a cruising\nrange of 13,000 miles. The extended\ncruising radius v.\u2019ill enable them to\nmake a trans-Pacific crossing and\nreturn without refueling. Similar\ntankers now operate at approx\nimately 12 1-2 knots and can cruise\nbetween 3,000 and 6,000 miles with\nout refueling. The new boats will\nhave a top speed of 18 knots.\nIncreased Speed\nIn addition to increased speed and\ncruising range, the vessels will carry\nammunition magazine spaces, gun\nfoundations, navy searchlights, a\nspecial protection against mines and\nincreased \u201cfloatability\u201d in case bulk\nheads are pierced by shells. The\nfour shipyards awarded contracts,\neach of which will build three of\n1 the tankers, are the Newport News\nShipbuilding and Drydock Co., News\nport News, Va.; Bethlehem Ship\nbuilding Corp. (Baltimore yard):\nSun Shipbuilding and Dry Dock\ncompany, Chester, Pa., and Federal\nShipbuilding and Dry Dock company\nj Kearney, N. J.\nSWEETHEART OF\nBANDIT SOUGHT\nStoneham, Mass.. Jan. 4.\u2014(UP)\u2014\nG-men today sought a slain ban\ndit\u2019s sweetheart as an alleged par\nticipant in the kidnaping and\nj shooting of a Portsmouth, N. H..\ntaxi driver.\nFederal agents Joined police of:\neastern cities in the hunt for\nblonde Ruth Freedman, 25, after\nthe victim, Robert Stickles, said\nhe believed j one of the five persons\n4.\nBank Debits\n70\n1 This is an important measure of business activity. Almost every\nbusiness deal is reflected at some point in a bank transaction.\nBank debits\u2014bank withdrawals\u2014have been rising since 1933. This chart\nreveals the singular fact that they began to fall off in April. The January\ndecline was natural. They have been declining ever since. They ended\nthe year around the Christmas, 1934, level.\n900\nSecurity Financing\u2014Public and Private\nThis chart should be studied carefully. It tells the remainder of\nthe story. It Is from the issue of new securities\u2014government and\ncorporation\u2014that new funds flow into the business world. This chart\nshows the total of all state, local, federal and private securities issued\neach month. The volume increased each month and rose to its peak in\nthe summrr of 1936. If that had continued to rise the recovery might\nhave continued. But a single glance will show by following the dotted\nline that for 15 monuths the volume has declined, and the decline has\nbeen heavy. Why? The answer to this is the answer to the whole riddle.\nLook at the black spaces at the bottom of this chart. They represent\nprivate corporate financing. The rest indicate government financing\u2014\ngovernment deficits\u2014state and federal, mostly federal. See how private\nfinancing has utterly failed. Before we can have the revival we- must\nhave a revival of financing. Either private business must start financing\noperations or the government must. There is no alternative. This is the\nkey to the future.\nAll-Time Record In\nGas Appliance Sales\nI\nCompanies in Connecticut Experience Year of Notable.\nAchievements, Says New Haven Executive\nDescribing 1937 as a year of no\ntable accomplishment by the gas\ncompanies of Connecticut, with in\ncreases in customers, gas sales and\nrevenues and an all-time record in\nthe sale of gas appliances, H. R.\nSterrett, president of the New Ha\ni\u2019en Gas Light company, in a resume\nof year-end conditions in the gas\nindustry predicted that, unless the\npresent recession exceeds current\npredictions, more gas and more gas\nappliances will be sold in Connecti\ncut in 1938 than in any previous\nyear.\nNotable Achievements\nMr. Sterrett's statement follows:\n\"Nineteen hundred and thirty\nseven has been a year of notable\naccomplishment by the gas compa\nnies in Connecticut. The number of\ngas consumers, the puantity of gas\nsold, and the revenue from same\nhave all exceeded 1936 figures, and\nthe sale of gas appliances in 1937\nestablished an all-time record.\n\"Despite the changing habits ol\nthe general populace, such as the\ndecided increase in the use of pre\npared foods, the growing habits of\neating out\u2019 and of doing less laun\ndry work at home, the greater fre\nquency of week-end holidays, and\nthe greatly improved efficiency of\nthe new gas ranges and water meat\ners,\u2014the use of gas for domestic\npurposes in the home has shown\nan increase. Interest in the use of\ngas for heatinng homes, stores and\nother places of business is growing\ntremendously with that of other\nruels. Even with the extremely mild\nweather of last winter the quantity\nof gas used for heating has shown\na very substantial and increase. The\ngreatest gain in the use of gas in\n1937 occurred in the industrial and\ncommercial fie!4s where, because ol\nits cleanliness, uniformity, economy\nand ease of control, gas is becoming\nIncreasingly popular.\n\"Remarkable advances have been\nmade in the performance of gas ap\npliances. No olnger can the claim\nbe upheld that gas kitchens are in\nferior, for today the modern gas\nkitchens are models of cleanliness\nand beauty. They automatically\nproduce a standard of cooking that\nIs unequalled,\u2014and they do it more\neconomically. The gas refrigerator\nhas gained wide-spread public ac\neeptance and enjoyed an extraordin\nary increase in sales during 1937.\nwho kidnaped him last April was a\nvoman dressed in man\u2019s clothing.\nStickles positively identified Sid\nney Power, 28. slain in a New Year\u2019s\neve holdup attempt here, as the\nkidnaper who shot him in the leg\nand forced him to drive at gun\npoint from Portsmouth, N. H., to\nSomerville. Mass. Power and Mts.\nFreedman had been living in a Bos\nton apartment as man and wife\nsince October, Police said,\nG-men also sought Melvin Ja\nqulth, 25, of Boston, believed Pow\nsr\u2019s companion in the fatal holdup\nattempt, as a possible participant In\nthe Stickles kidnaping.\n\u201cThe gas industry has awakened\nand by its spontaneous and wide\nspread support of such national\nprojects as the Mystery Chef broad\ncasts, the three-year national ad\nvertising campaign, the national\nHome Planning program, and the\n$1,000,000 \u2018Gas Industries\u2019 exhibit at\nthe coming New York world's fair.\u2014\ngives conclusive evidence that a new\nera in gas development is dawning.\nUnless the current business recession\nexceeds present predictions, more\ngas and more gas appliances should\nbe sold in Connecticut during 1938\nthan in any previous year.\u201d\nJIMMY FIDDLER\nIS FACING SUIT\nConstance Bennett De=\nmands $20,000 as Dam=\nages for Alleged Libel\nHolyywood, Jan. 4\u2014(UP)\u2014Con\nstance Bennett today demanded\n$250,000 damages from the radio\nmovie commentator Jimmy Pidler\nand his sponsors, whom she accused\nof libeling her in a broadcast. She\nsaid the broadcast falsely described\na feud between her and Patsy Kel\nly, another actress working in her\npicture. There was no feud, she\nsaid. Miss Bennett once was the\nhighest paid actress. She earned\n$30,000 a week for 10 weeks.\nFidler, she said, \u201cheld her up to\npublic hatred and ridicule\u201d by\nbroadcasting on Dec. 28 over a na\ntionwide network as follows:\n\u201cA tense situation has developed\nat the Hal Roach studios between\nConstance Bennett and Patsy Kelly.\nIt seems that when Patsy came to\nj work the first day, Connie said:\n\u2018I\u2019m .glad to have you in my pic\nture,\u2019 but the second day for some\nunaccountable reason, Miss Bennett\nfailed to speak to Miss Kelly at all.\nSided With Miss Kelly\n\u201cIt became so noticeable that\nstudio electricians and workers,\nsiding with Miss Kelly, began say\ning \u2018Hello Patsy,\u201d and they kept\nit up the entire day, either in fun\nor else to make pointed digs at\nMiss Bennett. \u201cThe workmen finally\nfinished things up in grand style\nwhen they presented Miss Kelly\nwith a large basket of flowers, but\nnone for Miss Bennett.\u201d\nMiss Bennett charged that thous\nands of her movie and radio fans\nwere made to believe that she was\n\u201cungracious and unfair\u201d to Miss\nKelly, who is a brunette comed\niene from Brooklyn. Those named\nin addition to Fidler were Proctor!\nGamble, the program sponsors,\nand the National Broadcasting com\npany. Fidler said he would oppose\nthe suit.\n1\nBALANCING OF\nBUDGET REMOTE\nPresident Cannot See Any\nEarly Hope Just at\nPresent Time\nBy LYLE C. WILSON\n(United Press Staff Correspondent)\nWashington, Jan. 4\u2014(UP)\u2014Presi\ndent Roosevelt went back today to\nthe last year of his second term\nas the earliest moment in which the\nunprecedented series of deficits can\nbe checked and the federal budget\nfinally balanced. He will submit his\n1939 budget to Congress tomorrow.\nThere is no assurance of budget\nbalance even in 1940. But it does\nappear reasonably certain now that\nthe purely fiscal record of the two\nRoosevelt administrations will be an\nunprecedented sequence of. treasury\ndeficits.\nHoover Started It\nFormer President Hoover\u2019s admin\nistration started the treasury into\nthe red in the fiscal year 1931.\nThere have been deficits every\nyear since then and Mr. Roosevelt\ninformed congress yesterday that he\nhad abandoned hope of balancing\nthe 1939 fiscal year budget.\nBudget balancing prospects van\nished under pressure of business re\ncession, demands for flood and em\nergency farm relief, and imminent\nnecessity to step up naval construc\ntion for national defense. Recovery\nand relief figures were revised up\nward to $1,876,000,000 for this year\nand may go considerably beyond\nthat figure if unemployment reach\nes the late-winter figure of 11,000,\n000 persons toward which it is\nheaded.\nTreasury Revenue Drops\nEstimates of treasury revenue\nwere revised sharply downward as\nrecession cut into business profits.\nMr. Roosevelt estimated in October\nthat congress in 1937 had imposed\nadditional budget unbalancing ex\npenditures of approximately $344.\n000,000 upon the treasury. Plans for\nearly budget balancing, therefore,\nli8ve been scrapped. Mr. Roosevelt\nreported to congress yesterday in his\nannual message only that the size\nof deficits was diminishing although\nthe treasury will remain in the red\nwhen this fiscal year ends next\nJune 30 and 18 months hence when\nthe next fiscal year ends on June\n30, 1939. Actual balance of the bud\nget for a complete fiscal year is\npostponed now for a minimum of\n30 months\u2014to June 30, 1940. when\nthe nation will be swinging into a\npresidential campaign.\nDISEASE IMPERIALS\nTOBACCO INDUSTRY\nConnecticut Growers Unite\nin Campaign to Check\n\u201cDowny Mildew\u201d\n(Special to The Democrat)\nHartford, Conn., Jan. 4\u2014An edu\ncational program to inform tobacco\ngrowers of the best methods to pre\nvent or control downy mildew of to\nbacco, deadly disease new in Con\nnecticut last spring, has been ar\nranged during December and Jan- j\nuary. Cooperating agencies are the i\nHartford County Farm Bureau and\nthe Tobbacco Substation at Wind\nsor. Meetings have been held in the\ntowns of Suffleld, Ellington and\nSouth Windsor. The January sched\nule has not yet been made At the\nsame meetings J. S. Owens of the\nextension service will speak on\n\u201cFertilizing the Tobacco Crop.\u201d\nNearly every grower is familiar\nwith the appearance of downy mil\ndew in the seedbeds.\nDoctor P. J. Anderson, in charge\nof the substation at Windsor, plans\nto discuss methods of control de\nscribed in his new bulletin on the\ndisease, number 405 of the experi\nment station series, which is ready\nfor distribution this week. Copies\nare being sent to tobacco growers\nwhose names are listed at the sta\ntion and to other citizens of Con\nnecticut on request.\nDowny mildew is a fungus dis\nease. Doctor Anderson writes, that\nhas been so serious in Australia as\nnearly to wipe out the tobacco in\ndustry. It has also been widespread\nin the South of this country where\nlosses have been severe. The author\nhas studied reports from other\nplaces and was watching for the\nappearance of downy mildew in\nConnecticut when the first case was\nreported late in the seedbed season\nof 1937. In a few weeks it spread\nto all sections of the Connecticut\nValley. In contrast to habits in\nother parts of the United States, the\ndisease was found also in the fields\nwhen the plants had been set out,\nbut disappeared during the hot, dry\nspell in July. Because it arrived so\nlate, (the actual loss to growers was\nnot large. However, now that it has\na foothold in Connecticut, Doctor\nAndersn points out that it is likely\nto reappear and that it may do con\nsiderable injury another season.\nBulletin 405 discusses the symp\ntoms of the disease, the casual para\nsites, other plant hosts, the source\nof infection in the spring, how\nweather affects mildew, and meth\nods of prevention and control.\nThe meetings are open to the\npublic and the bulletins are dis\ntributed free to residents of the\nstate.\nGERMAN COUNT IS\nNOT TO LECTURE\nBerlin, Jan. 4\u2014(UP)\u2014Count Her\nmann Keyserling, philosopher and\nwriter, has cancelled a lecture en\ngagement in the United States on\nthe \"advice\u201d of the Gestapo, the\nNazi secret police, it was learned\ntoday. Count Keyserling was to have\nsailed for New York late in Decem\nber to fulfill a lecture tour engage\nment. Two weeks before his sailing\ndate, it was learned, he was \u201cad\nvised\u201d not to go.\nThe first reports of the cancella\ntion came last night. They said\nthat \u201cfor reasons of health\u201d the\ncount had decided to cancel. Then\nit was added that it appeared\ndoubtful whether he would be able'\nto accept an invitation for a later\ndate. As the count is in the Black\nForest, apparently In good health,\nthis statement caused speculation.\nCount Keyserling last lectured In\nMarket Opens Steady\nWith Greater Volume\nMost Leaders Registered Gains at Outset\u2014Cotton\nFutures Higher; U. S. Steel Had Sharp, Strong Rise\nBy ELMER C. WALZER\n(United Press Financial Editor)\nNew York, Jan. 4^-(UP)\u2014Stocks\nwere steady today with volume in\ncreased. Most leaders registered\nsmall gains at the outset. Braids\nwere firm. Cotton futures were 3\npoints higher to 2 lower.\n1:15 P. M. PRICES\nWHITEHOUSE CO.\nAllied Chem. 164\nAm. Can 73%\nAm. Sm. Ref. 48\nAm. Tel. Tel. 145 'fe\nAllied Stores 6%\nAnaconda Cop. 30%\nAtch. Top. S. F. 36\nBalt. Ohio 9%\nBeth. Steel 61%\nBorden 17%\nCan. Pacific 7%\nCase Mach. 84\nChes. Ohio 34%\nChrysler Motor 49%\nConsolidated Oil. 29%\nCon. Edison 23\nContinental Can. 39\nDuPont. 112%\nElec. Auto-Lite 15%\nGeneral Elec. 42\nGeneral Foods 30%\nGeneral Motors. 31%\nGoodyear 18%\nInt i. Tel. TeL 6%\nJohns Manville 76%\nKennecot Cop. 36\nKresge Stores. 16\nLoews 46\nMcKesson Robbins 6%\nMack Truck 19\nMont. Ward 31%\nNash Kelvinator. 10%\nNat\u2019l. Biscuit 18%\nNat\u2019l. Dairy 13%\nN. Y. Central 16%\nNew Haven R. R. 2%\nNorth Am. 19%\nPenn. R. R. 21%\nPub. Ser. of N. J. 32\nPullman Co. 30%\nRadio 6%\nRep. Iron Steel 17%\nSears-Roebuck. 55\nSouth Pac. 18%\nStandard Brands 8%\nS. O. of N. J. 47\nSocony-Vacuum 15\nStewart-Wamer 8%\nStudebaker 5%\nTexas Corp. 39\nTexas Gulf 27%\nUnion Carbide. 73%\nUnion Pacific 82%\nUnited Air 26\nUnited Corp.. 31 -j\nUnited Gas Improved 10%\nU. S. Indus. Alcohol 20\nU. S. Rubber 23%\nU. S. Steel 56%\nVanadium 16\nWarner Bros. 6%\nWestern Union 24\nWestinghouse Elec. 102%\nWool worth. 37\nNEW YORK CURB\nAmer. Superpower 1\nCities Service 2\nElec. Bond Share 9'i\nNiagara Hudson Power 7U\nN. Y. B<uk Trust Stocks\nThe R. F. Griggs Co.\nBid Asked\nBank of Manhattan 21 24\nBank of N. Y. <5: Trust. .345 365\nBankers Trust 47*,a 50'i\nCent. Hanover Bank\nTrust'. 89 92\nChase National Bank 31 34\nChemical Bank Trust 43 46\nCorn Exchange Bank 49 52\nEmpire Trust 20 23\nFirst National Bank 1750 1850\nGuaranty Trust .232 241\nIrving Trust 1012Va\nManufacturers Trust 33 36\nNational City Bank _ 27 30\nNew York Trust 92 95 1\nTitle Guarantee Trust 6 8\nMEXICAN CABINET\nIS REORGANIZED\nMexico City. Jan. 4. (UP)\u2014A j\ndrastic reorganization of the Mexi-\ncan cabinet became effective today\nas Presidet Lazaro Cardenas I\nstrengthened his new conciliatory j\ntoward business.\nAs outlined in his New Year\u2019s day\nmessage to the nation, Cardenas re\ncalled that government policies dur\ning the first half of his administra\ntion had been directed largely to\nward improvement of farm condi\ntions but that the next three years\nwould be devoted to stressing the\nneed of industrialization in Mexico.\nSilvestre Guerrero resigned as\nminister of interior, highest ranking\npost in the cabine, and was re\nplaced by Ignacio Garcia Tellez,\nCardenas private secretary.\nThe second most important post,\nthat of secretary of war, is held by i\nGeneral Avila Camacho, who took\noffice on New Year\u2019s day.\nGeneral Rafael Sanchez Tapia\nresigned as secretary of national\neconomy and was succeeded by\nEfrain Buenrostro, who had held\nthe post of undersecretary of\nfinance.\nPROF. ROBINSON DIES\nProvidence, R. I., Jan. 4.\u2014(UP)\u2014\nProfessor Thomas Herbert Robin\nson, head of the English department\nat Rhode Island College of Educa\ntion, died yesterday at his home.\nBefore joining the Rhode Island\nfaculty in 1926, he taught at Water\nbury, Conn., high school and State\nNormal Training School, Potsdam,.\nN. Y. A native of Waterbury, he\nleaves a wife, father and sister.\nServices will be held Thursday.\nBerlin, Nov. 1. Then, addressing an\naudience of prominent people in\ncluding members of the aristocracy\non \u201cinner experience and outward\nfate,\u201d he said that the grandfath\ners of the men who are young today\nhad lots of initiative.\nFor COMPLETE Market*\nand Financial News\nRelied upon by business men\nand investors everywhere.\nSend.for free sample copy.\nTHE WALL STREET JOURNAL\n4* Broad St New lock\n0\u2014.1.1 W\u2014\nWestinghouse Electric opened at\n100 3-4 up 1 5-8 and Sears Roebuc